<h2>Overview</h2><p>If you’re looking to enhance the look and functionality of your JK or JKU Jeep Wrangler, installing Smittybilt XRC Fender Flares is a great modification. In this guide, we’ll walk you through the process of removing the rear fender flares and installing the new ones, a crucial part of part two of our three-part series. With affordable pricing and excellent clearance, these flares offer both style and practicality for off-road enthusiasts.</p><h2>What This Covers</h2><p>This article elaborates on the steps for removing the factory rear fender flares and installing the Smittybilt XRC fender flares. We will also touch on important considerations, necessary tools, and tips for ensuring a smooth installation process.</p><h2>Step-by-Step Breakdown</h2><ol><li><strong>Gather Your Tools:</strong> Before you start, ensure you have the necessary tools: a ratchet set, screwdriver, and possibly a cutting tool if adjustments are needed.</li><li><strong>Remove Factory Flares:</strong> Carefully remove the screws and clips holding the factory rear fender flares in place. A word of caution—be gentle to avoid scratching the paint underneath.</li><li><strong>Prepare the Surface:</strong> Once the old flares are off, clean the area thoroughly to ensure a good grip for the new flares.</li><li><strong>Install New Flares:</strong> Position the Smittybilt flares and attach them using the provided screws. Note that some new holes will need to be drilled, which is different from the installation process for the front flares.</li><li><strong>Final Adjustments:</strong> Ensure the flares are aligned and secure. If you're using fender liners, this is the moment to install them as well.</li><li><strong>Check the Overall Look:</strong> Step back and admire your work. The new fender flares should significantly change the appearance of your Jeep.</li></ol><h2>Helpful Tips</h2><ul><li>Consider whether you want to use fender liners; many opt out, but they can protect your Jeep's underbody.</li><li>Make sure you have a solid plan for removing any broken clips; some might not come off cleanly.</li><li>It may require some improvisation with cutting to make everything fit just right, so keep that in mind before starting.</li></ul><h2>Key Takeaways</h2><p>Installing Smittybilt XRC Fender Flares is a valuable modification for any JK or JKU Wrangler owner looking to upgrade both aesthetics and utility. This tutorial helps ensure your installation goes smoothly, transforming your vehicle’s look while improving clearance for off-road adventures. Remember to take your time, gather the right tools, and enjoy the process of giving your Jeep a fresh new style!</p>

